'''James Anderson''' ({{floruit}} 1865–1870) was a [[Protestant]] [[Christian]] missionary who served with the [[London Missionary Society]] during the late [[Qing Dynasty]] [[China]].  He entered the country in [[Hong Kong]] on 27 December 1865 and continued on to [[Guangzhou|Canton]] in 1867<ref>{{cite book |title=Memorials of Protestant Missionaries to the Chinese |publisher=American Presbyterian Mission Press |location=Shanghai |year=1867 |page=275}}</ref> where he remained through 1870.<ref>{{cite book |title=The China Mission Hand-book |publisher=American Presbyterian Mission Press |location=Shanghai |year=1896 |page=5 |isbn=0-524-06868-2}}</ref> He and his wife left for England on 5 May 1870 for health reasons.<ref>{{cite journal |journal=The Chinese Recorder and Missionary Journal |volume=3 |date=June 1870 |first=Justus |last=Doolittle |pages=28 |title=Missionary Intelligence |issue=1}}</ref>

