 --> | postal_code = | area_code = | website = | footnotes = }} '''Kafr Hawr''' ({{lang-ar|كفر حور}}; also spelled '''Kafr Hawar''' or '''Kafr Hur''') is a [[Syria]]n village situated {{convert|35|km|mi}} southwest of [[Damascus]].<ref name="Division1920">{{cite book|author=Great Britain. Naval Intelligence Division|title=A handbook of Syria: including Palestine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6ITVAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=23 September 2012|year=1920|publisher=H.M. Stationery Office}}</ref><ref name="HouraniHeyda1983">{{cite book|author1=May M. Hourani|author2=Charles M. Heyda|author3=United States Board on Geographic Names |author4=United States Defense Mapping Agency |title=Gazetteer of Syria: names approved by the United States Board on Geographic Names|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ou8fwBn66UwC|accessdate=23 September 2012|year=1983|publisher=Defense Mapping Agency}}</ref> According to the [[Central Bureau of Statistics (Syria)|Syria Central Bureau of Statistics]], the village had a population of 2,957 in the 2004 census.<ref name="CBS">[https://archive.is/20130112152953/http://www.cbssyr.org/new%20web%20site/General_census/census_2004/NH/TAB03-33-2004.htm General Census of Population and Housing 2004]. [[Central Bureau of Statistics (Syria)|Syria Central Bureau of Statistics]] (CBS). Rif Dimashq Governorate. {{ar icon}}</ref>
The village is built into the side of a hill near [[Mount Hermon]], just north of modern day [[Hinah]], which was an ancient settlement mentioned by [[Ptolemy]] as being called Ina.<ref name="SmithBartholomew1915">{{cite book|author1=Sir George Adam Smith|author2=John George Bartholomew|title=Atlas of the Historical Geography of the Holy Land|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5FMzAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=23 September 2012|year=1915|publisher=Hodder & Stoughton}}</ref> It sits opposite a village called [[Beitima]] across a valley through which flows the River 'Arny.<ref name="Fund1920">{{cite book|author=Palestine Exploration Fund|title=Quarterly statement - Palestine Exploration Fund|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LLo9AAAAMAAJ|accessdate=23 September 2012|year=1920}}</ref>
==Korsei el-Debb Roman temple== There is a [[Roman temple]] in the area called '''Korsei el-Debb''' that is one of a group of [[Temples of Mount Hermon]].<ref name="Kaizer2008">{{cite book|author=Ted Kaizer|title=The Variety of Local Religious Life in the Near East In the Hellenistic and Roman Periods|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KgVD3WL0vAsC&pg=PA76|accessdate=23 September 2012|year=2008|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-16735-3|pages=76–}}</ref> [[Louis Felicien de Saulcy|Félicien de Saulcy]] suggested the temple was originally constructed entirely of white [[marble]]. A marble block was found featuring a dedication to a goddess called [[Hierapolis]] (also identified as [[Atargatis]] and [[Leukothea]]).<ref name="ChaniotisCorsten2006">{{cite book|author1=A. Chaniotis|author2=T. Corsten|author3=R. S. Stroud|author4=R. A. Tybout|title=Supplementum Epigraphicum Graecum|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wooaAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=23 September 2012|date=30 August 2006|publisher=Brill Academic Pub|isbn=978-90-04-15508-4}}</ref><ref name="Schmitt1995">{{cite book|author=Götz Schmitt|title=Siedlungen Palästinas in griechisch-römischer Zeit|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xXJtAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=23 September 2012|year=1995|publisher=Dr. Ludwig Reichert Verlag|isbn=978-3-88226-820-1}}</ref>
